segments.text: Okay, you were giving impressions of Dr. Calhoun.
My relationship with him started in the early 60s, and the Department of Commerce, the U.S.
Department of Commerce started what they called an Office of Technical Services, MTS.
And what they would do is they would provide you funding to answer inquiries from industry in your state.
So Dr. Calhoun created at that time what he called the State Technical Services Institute.
He asked me to serve as director of that, which I did.
And so I had some connection with him, but the real connection, I guess, was when the Seagrant program got down there.
I had quite a hunk of that Seagrant program at one time, and that come down there in the late 60s as well as I remember.
It had to be before, say, the three.
And I did a lot of work with the Seagrant program.
because I used my industrial economics staff and stood in perfect to do all economic studies along the coast and things of that nature.
And OTS had gone out of business, by the way.
Office of Technical Services had gone out of business, and then I got in on the Seagrass program.
So that's really the period between 65 and 73 is when I got well acquainted.
Make believe that I had never seen
John Calhoun, describe him physically and his style of, I wish I had a picture, I could just give it to you.
Dr. Calhoun was probably the most diversified and intelligent individual I had in my life.
Dr. Calhoun could grasp things rapidly.
I don't know whether he did a lot of reading on these things before I come in contact with him or not, but he was always very well versed.
My experience with him was through the state technical institute and through the C grant program.
And I always felt that Dr. Calhoun was a very easy person to talk to.
I never have seen Dr. Calhoun.
Now, some people have told me they've seen Dr. Calhoun bad.
I've never seen him bad.
Never had in my life.
But we've become pretty close to doing those years on different things.
We attended a lot of conferences together.
I did a lot of studies.
And then one day out of a clear blue sky in 1973, on a Thursday afternoon, I was working away, and I got this phone call.
It was Dr. Whitman.
And Dr. Williams said, Jim, I've told you before, I was having my industrial conference start Monday, and I had the governor coming over to get the welcome address that I had every year.
And Dr. Williams said, Jim, I'd like to come in with you for a few minutes.
I went on down to the office, and after about five minutes of shaking hands, he said, you know, we have a vacancy as a director meeting in the taking service.
that we want to create in the Office of Continuing Education."
And he says, I'd like for you to get those folks.
Tell me about this man, Jack Williams.
Well, of course, Jack Williams and Dr. Calhoun were very close.
I mean, business-wise, I don't know if I've played a lot, but they had a lot of respect for each other.
So, I said, well, Dr. Williams, I didn't even know there was a place.
I had the job that I really enjoyed.

getting bigger every day and getting more statewide and that's the recognition i said i i'd have to think about it a little bit he said well what do you do you need anything to think about i said yes i said i want to copy the budget i said i want to see what kind of budget they have where the sources of money is coming from so he got on the phone and he called fred benson if i'm not mistaken it might have been calvin but he called somebody
and told me I'd like for you to get some budgets up here for the Internet Pension Service.
And so he got them.
How'd of that happen?
And so we just did a few minutes.
He said, go.
When do you think we can get back together?
I said, we'll get back here Monday morning.
I said, I'll have all Saturday.
I said, we'll get back Monday morning.
So he said, well, just give me a ring Monday morning when you're ready.
And I did.
I didn't get to him until about 3 o'clock that afternoon.
But I went there and I told him what my problem was.
And I had, you know, if I could do anything.
You know, if I'm going to do this, I need this, I need this, I need this, I need this, I need this, this, this, this.
Got down to the bottom line.
The most important thing, I had to have total control of all the people in the organization.
And if I was going to be fair with them, I was going to evaluate each one.
But if they didn't fit into the organization, if I'm going to plan for this, then we're going to have to find somebody that will feel like it's possible.
But anyway, it went on like that.
And I had a list pretty long when I got to do it.
He says, is that all?
And I said, yes, sir.
You haven't asked for nothing.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing.
He said, no, I think.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing.
You can't get it.
And so I said, OK.
So then he called Fred Benson in Calhoun.
As far as you know, he had talked with each of them in depth.
Oh, I'm quite sure of that.
And another thing I had, see I had a lot of research projects in that industry, and this was in August when he called me in.
And I told him, I said, I couldn't possibly accept the job for December 12th.
Because I had sponsors out here that supported me for years.
And I said, well, that'd be fun.
Describe the extension service when you took over.
What was it?
How big was it?
Where was it?
Well, it was in the old American Legion Hall.
Bob Whitewood before you moved out there.
That used to be just an old building there.
Do you remember that, or was it already down when you got here?
Do you remember where the headquarters of Bob White was up until just about a year ago?
No, I don't.
Well, you know where the Farmer Student Association building is now?
It used to be that old wooden building right across the street.
Oh, across the street, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.
Over there by the police station.
Well, I didn't know anybody
I didn't know anybody in India and Pennsylvania except Ernie Winacek.
The only reason I knew him, he had more than my age.
And I had met him through Buddy Williams.
And Buddy Williams, he and Ernie were pretty good friends.
But he's the only one I knew.
And so when I took over, they took action at the October board meeting.
We had all been making a motion, Ms.
Wilson Sutton.
This is 73?
No, it's 70.
Yes, 73.
I forgot to go to the 71st of 73.
But this meeting was in October before meeting.
And so when that was announced, it would come out in the paper and everything.
And by the day, well, by the way, Dr. Knight, you know, the Dean of Medicine, was approved the same day I was approved to the Institute of Nutrition Service.
His pitch is on the front page of these on one side and mine is on the other.
And I just saw what they fixed, that monument, whatever it was.
When I went over to the Engineering Extension Service, it had a budget of about $1.5 million and they had about $50 million.
Where were they based?
All of them here?
Yeah, at that time.
They weren't up to date.
There was not an area that you could find that they would have to date on.
They taught without lesson plans.
They didn't have any technical manuals.
It's a training organization.
But they have 51 employees and about a little over, about a million and a half dollar budget.
But their budget come, one-third come from Texas Education Agency, one-third come directly from appropriations, and then they've got one-third of their budget from the future.
And that was the third, third, and third.
Well, you've got to realize, engineering intensive service was an old organization.
And most of the employees were in there, you know, since their first job.
Anyway, when it was announced, they had Dr. Mansfield, who was the social director.
And that was the final person, if you ever want to meet the partner.
But he had been led to believe either through himself or through Mr. Bearden.
See, Mr. Bearden had been director, and he retired, that he was going to be the director.
Well, by the way, when I've become director, I'll have to do it.
But anyway, and all of them in the Indian Attention Service was, you know, shocked that he didn't get it.
So, the first day I took over, December the 1st, 1973, I stayed away from that until
My wife went in for her third malignancy surgery.
She was operating on that board the first day I took over.
Two important events.
Very important events.
I stayed with my wife.
I called Dr. Cowen, which I don't know where I called her, but anyway, they knew where I was at.
And I stayed with her all that day, with Dr. McQuaid.
And we had a doctor out of Houston come up, and that was her third surgery.
So after they got through with the surgery, it was in about five hours, Dr. Quaid came out and told him, he said, I don't have my phone for you.
And he said, we're going to send her down to Houston and start taking chemotherapy.
I'm not going to dwell on this.
Anyway, after the third operation, my wife had about all the operations she'd wanted.
But anyway, they made an appointment for me to go see this doctor down at the Kent's hospital in Houston.
And I got her.
We had an appointment at 1.30 in the afternoon with my wife, and I walked in, and I checked her and she shut the door.
I stayed outside.
In about 20 minutes, all 15 minutes, she'd come out and she'd come out.
I'm sorry.
I said, your wife won't let me touch her.
She said, she got me the tape from there.
Remember?
And he said, unless I get to examine it, he said, he doesn't look at me.
So we went in, he said, come on in.
I said, tell him for us that.
And I said, no, you sure you made up the money?
Yep.
I said, how much do I owe him?
He said, $35.
I wrote him a check, and that was in 1973.
Can you imagine that?
But going back to the same thing, that's true.
Where did, primarily geographically, where did,
When you took over, where were they doing the instruction that they were?
They were going out in motels.
No, but where was it?
Was it in the Houston area?
Oh, it was all over the state.
But it wasn't concentrated in one?
No, no.
Okay.
No, no.
See, they were doing all the training for rural electric co-ops and their linemen training and things of this nature.
They did a lot of training for the Texas Telephone Association.
See, they were getting subsidized.
Right.
Give more examples of that.
Okay, and law enforcement, all the state and law enforcement, water and wastewater.
They did all the training for water and wastewater in the cities.
Of course, we had the fire protection.
We had the extension part of it, and then we had the fire field.
Fireman Training Center was all part of that?
Oh, yeah.
That was the biggest part.
But they used volunteer instructors.
They only had four people on the full-time staff at the farm.
When they go to town, they'd just get somebody at the farm to volunteer.
Was there one client that was by far the key one, the biggest?
Was there?
Well, the Rural Electric Co-op, of course, the organization was so small, they only had 50, 55 people.
That's all I had with them.
But the Rural Electric Co-ops,
and the Texas Telephone Association, and the water departments of the cities, and the law enforcement and the law.
Those were your, it was all sizable buttons.
But to kind of put this thing in perspective, when I left there, we had 400 employees in a $39 million budget and was only getting $3 million in general revenue.
$36 million was coming in fees and contracts.
Now wait, give me those numbers again.
When I took over, it was around 51, I think, employees, about 2.5 million.
When I left on December, I mean, on January the 31st, 1992, we had a $39 million budget, and we had 400 employees.
And of that budget, how much did y'all... Ten percent.
We got three million and something in general revenue, and the rest you brought in.
That was in fees and contracts.
All right.
When you started out, you were primarily serving small-town needs,
rural areas and city water departments in your small town city water departments, small town law enforcement.
And the telephone companies were the co-ops?
Rural telephones.
Rural telephones.
Alright, let's see.
When you took over, were there any key office staff members that you came to rely on?
I'm talking about the people in the office.
I lined them up real fast.
I had to bring them in.
As I told you, Dr. Mansfield was a fine person, and there must have been a shock to his system, because he had never heard of me, and I never heard of him.
And of course, he just never would.
Well, he had a different philosophy.
His philosophy and my philosophy was up completely 100% different.
I was used to the soft money operation.
I've always had the soft money operation.
I liked it.
It gave me a lot of latitude.
They didn't like it.
It was a threat to their jobs.
It was a threat to their jobs.
So, but then another thing I asked Dr. Williams when I took over, I had to have a new headquarters office.
I had to have another office.

But anyway, I never did go down to that, but I was up on the eighth floor at the top, because that's where I had the production of continuing education, and I had that whole eighth floor in the tower.
Of the rudder tower?
Yeah.
So, that's where, that was my headquarters for both offices, continuing education.
All right, when you took over,
In terms of reporting, you reported to?
Dr. Calhoun and Fred Benson.
In which order?
I did.
All three of us worked very well.
All right.
On paper, was it to Benson, or was it to both on paper?
Both of them.
Okay.
See, I got funding from Virginia Education at Texas A&M University.
All right, let's go back and talk about this man, Benson.
He's a Kenzan, I think, didn't he?
Ken State.
And tell me about his working style and so forth.
Well, you never did leave a meeting with Fred Benson that you didn't know where he stood.
He wasn't a bit bashful to pick up the phone and say, Jim, what's this I hear about so-and-so's?
You'd explain it to him.
That was the end of it, I guess, for me at all, of course.
You know, we had our ground rules.
I said my ground rules with him, and the captain said, what do you expect?
What kind of report do you want?
What kind of, when do you want me to inform you of something?
Give me some guidelines, because I don't have time to tell you everything I do, and you don't have time to listen to everything I do.
Give me your guidelines.
You know what Mr. Benson's answer was that?
keep me informed on a matter you think that I should have some input on.
I never called him.
Not that, you know, I just never had a reason.
I could say the same thing about Calvary.
All right, now officially, the Extension Engineering Extension Service was part of the Texas A&M University and of the system.
No, the Engineering Extension Service.
It was always a part of the system.
All right.
During those years with Williams and Calhoun and Benson, did it matter, system or campus?
Did it matter?
And how you operated?
Not with me.
It didn't matter because I knew exactly what the system was supposed to do.
I knew the policies and procedures of the system.
And I knew what the university was supposed to do.
And I knew exactly what I was expected of me in the university and knew exactly what they expected me in the university.
When you wanted to communicate with them
Whom did you have to go through to get to Calhoun or to Benson?
Nobody except the secretary.
They all, you always, he had the same, they had the same thing with me.
I mean, we never, I never had one minute that I ever thought.
All right, as you think back on those first years, what were some key decisions that were made by you or anybody else?
or pertaining to the work of the Extension Service?
Well, I'm not being derogatory because I make this statement, but I had to have people that would grow.
I had maybe two people with college degrees.
Dr. Mansfield had his degree, and they might have one or two others out there.
The rest of them was all non-degree people.
They had one title that was all called
So, my first thing that I did when I went in there, by January the 1st, I had a study conducted on what their title should be.
They told me exactly what their qualifications should be, as far as education, experience, and everything.
And I even had no pay range.
Everybody made the same.
If you're an instructor, you make the same.
Or give or take.

So the first thing we did, we'd give them something to, and then in February of that year, I had a meeting in Wine Deal with the whole staff, a day and a half, two days of meeting, at which time I'd give them a copy of what I call management by objective, and how we was going to run anything services, what part they were going to play, what was expected of it, and so forth and so on.
And that didn't go too well, though.
But anyway, there was a few.
You know, they really didn't touch it.
But you've got to remember, this was an old organization.
They had all been in together.
Here's a damn strange investment.
But anyway, after we had that meeting, and none of them understood management at all.
They didn't know what management by objective was.
They didn't, you know, it just had never been explained.
But anyway, when we started putting that thing together, and then on June the 1st, I come into a recommendation with Dr. Williams.
This is for the Engineer Protection Service and a recommendation with Dr. Williams, who's Fred Benson.
I kept Fred informed on him.
He told me to take it to Dr. Williams on pay scale.
And they had about, I'd say they had about $500,000 in the service.
So we'd automatically, you know, if they had the qualifications, they'd go into this pay status.
to find somebody who had those cross missions and so forth.
So we'd give them each title, training specialist, associate training specialist, assistant training specialist, you know, give them to separate them.
But what was the question?
Well, it was about key decisions.
Okay.
That's how the decisions were made.
And then once we got that thing in line, then unfortunately Burrow got the plans, you know,
decided to take retirement.
He was about 65 years old.
And he decided to take retirement and took retirement and three days later died.
But he'd had bypass surgery.
So that moved that phase, whatever you want to call it, out.
And then I brought in a new man as associate director.
I brought in Milton Franklin, right off.
He was a young engineer.
How do you spell his last name?
He was a young man.
He was with TTI.
And how did he come about being in us?
TTI was getting into public works training.
Well, I had created a center for public works.
And I picked up the paper one Saturday morning.
There was TTI announcing that public works.
So, I got a hold of Fred.
I said, Fred, we've got a problem.
And I said, what's the problem?
I told him.
He said, I'll take care of that Monday morning.
So he had Jack Keese in the morning.
He could get out of public work.
That's an extension activity.
That's not a research activity.
And so Milton Rutkey was in that position for TPI.
So I just transferred him and one other TPI staff member.
And it turned out that Milton, he's a very good engineer, and a very smart individual, and a very, very good writer.
Hard work, very hard work.
So I brought him over.
So I said, director, well, that made all the rest of it.
Well, I didn't do it by at all.
He was there a year, a year and a half.
You know, I observed him for a time.
But that's how that got started.
But when you have to have a decision made, it took me less than five minutes to get it.
I could call Benson.
He'd say, well, what did you do?
Or what do you want to do?
Or I could call Calhoun.
And Calhoun wasn't as quick on the draw as Benson was, but he was still very quick.
You know what I mean?
I mean, I'd have more conversation with Calhoun than I would with Benson.
Did you ever get the impression that either one of them ever made a snap judgment without thinking it through?
I'm sure.
There are quite few of us.
I think everybody who's done their best done that.
Let's see.
Back to other decisions.
Because you're in charge for 19 years.
Other decisions that you now look back on and say, those were key decisions we made.
Well, one key decision we made, you always build on your strength.
We had a reputation in the fire department, all over the state of town.
I could contact every legislator with one phone call.
So I said, that's our face.
So the first thing I did, I put about $150,000 in that far.
And I said, look, we don't have any roads in here.
You know, we don't have any training aids out there or exhibits.
So I put that right on.
And that was located then where it is now, just east of Easterwood Airport.
Right.
And Calhoun was responsible for getting that location along before I took over to the detention center.
So we started building on that.
Then I said, okay, what's your second strength?
Well, my second strength was electronics, but I had a man in electronics that, you know, had no education to speak of, and so his name was Arthur Pat, a fine person.
All these people out of town are fine people, and that wasn't the problem with them, was that they didn't have the background to do what was necessary.
So I replaced him right off with Dr. Lloyd Fight.
F-I-T-E.
F-I-T-E.
He was Dick Winertis.
handyman, you can do it, you know?
So, Dick would already call me up one day.
He said, Jim, he said, Lloyd didn't get his tenure.
And he said, he said, you want to get out of the academic department?
He said, is there any way you can take him halftime?
I said, sure.
Well, I took Lloyd over there with halftime with understanding.
That was in February.
Halftime, September the 1st, you could go on a phone call.
And we had a degree with a nurse.
And so we then started leaning pretty heavy on electronics, and we got that thing built up.
We had a gentleman in the rural electric co-ops.
At one time, the same gentleman was over rural electric co-op training and the Texas Telephone Association training.
So when he retired, I saw that was my strength company.
In the meantime, I got to be very, very well-informed and acquainted with both
with people on the Texas Telephone Association board and the electric parties of the board.
And they were lobbying for me.
The real electric co-ops would take the engineering extension service with their lobbyists for funding.
And same thing with the Texas Telephone Association.
So I said, well, you know, that's a pro-therapy.
Maybe not real electric, but you know, you've got others.
So we started tying in with GTE.
Started tying in with several others.
Got all their training materials.
They'd give me every bit of their training materials, you could use, reproduce.
But at that time, see, none of my people had nothing, no training materials.
So we got that from the telephone train, from the Telltale.
Then we started getting the power train, electric power.
The real electric co-op didn't have any, but it used to light the power at that time, had plenty.
The big one that really helped me out on my electric train was Texas Power and Light.
It's now Texas Utility.
That's how we built the thing.
We took those growth areas.
And then after, you know, we valued, re-evalued them.
And if they had no growth potential, you know, you say, you know, we maybe ought to take them out, which we did.
We did away with three or four divisions.
What were they?
Oh, boy.
They were always one-man operations.
One, we had, well, one thing we did,
FIRE had to have this material, and I took that directly away from the FIRE.
I started to have this training, the whole division of it.
But Al Sterling, a very fine guy.
He was a Coast Guard colonel retiree.
He had his master's degree from MIT.
When he retired, we brought him up there with both divisions and put that under FIRE.
We did the same thing with management training.
We used to have two levels of management training.
One was for the very goal level thing.
So then we just started to get to the higher level, the supervisory training.
So we had to let, so I let that lower division just go.
We just started when I called supervisory training.
And I'm sure there's five or six others, but I didn't.
But we ended up, we started out, we had five divisions, and we ended up at 17.
Our staff to professionals first is the support staff, and we're about four to one.
Every professional has about one.
See, now that staff person had to do a lot of work while those people were traveling all along the state of town, and they had to have strong staff people.
But it was about four to one.
Where, in the areas where you all worked, in what area, what work area, subject area, was it easiest to raise money, and which one was most difficult to support?
It was all, there was no different.
Let me just tell you what.
We started centers about ten years after I got there, about the 78, 79, I put in my first center in San Antonio, called South Central Texas Regional Training Center.
And at that time, Henry Cisneros was on the city council, and then let him make a marriage.
And they had a program over there that was under the junior college, and they were totally unhappy.
The city funded it, and they were totally unhappy.
So the guy, the president of the Virginia College of America, Mr. Dr. Wieland, so they asked me to take it over.
I said, well, this is enough.
We've got as much as we want.
You know, I'll go talk to him.
Well, I don't know if I talk to him.
He was as happy as a lark to get it.
And he said, you can't get along with him.
But anyway, he had about a $300,000 a year program with him.
And so then when we took over the South Central Region Training Center, when they give us, you know, whenever I did anything like that, you know, I'll give everyone's with me.
You've got to provide me facilities.
And you know what I mean?
We can't rent them.
We don't mean that.
We mean we want facilities built.
If you want the engineering things to come in, we have to look the part to play the part.
And so we've got real nice facilities.
The city got an EDA grant, and the man in San Antonio gives 20 acres of land to build it on.
But anyway, we turned out to have a big thing.
So then when they redid the hemisphere area,
They wanted us to concentrate on electronics in that area so far.
They built this beautiful, big building, right there in the chemistry industry.
We had a 25-year lease, and before I left, I got two 25-year lease extensions, so that's 75 years.
When we put that in, that was our first cylinder.
And when I left that thing, it had about a $2 million year budget.
So then the next cylinder I went in was North Texas.
It was in Orlando.
We went all over Orlando.
And the next cylinder was in the West Texas area that was happening.
Now all these people were furnishing us, these facilities, and let's see, been used to it.
We went into the Houston area about the same time we went into
